That's a **Material Symbol "arrow_forward"** icon.

Since you're already using Thymeleaf and static resources, I would **not load Google Fonts just for one icon**. It's cleaner to download the SVG and keep it in your project.

### Option 1 (Recommended) - SVG Image

Download the SVG and put it in:

```text
src/main/resources/static/images/icons/arrow-forward.svg
```

Then update your button:

```html
<button type="submit" class="confirm-btn">
    Continue
    <img th:src="@{/images/icons/arrow-forward.svg}"
         alt=""
         class="btn-icon">
</button>
```

CSS:

```css
.confirm-btn {
    margin-top: 40px;
    height: 48px;
    padding: 0 24px;
    border: 0;
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: #073331;
    color: #ffffff;
    font-size: 16px;
    font-weight: 700;

    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;

    cursor: pointer;
}

.btn-icon {
    width: 20px;
    height: 20px;
    filter: brightness(0) invert(1);
}
```

---

### Option 2 - Inline SVG (Best Performance)

No extra file required.

```html
<button type="submit" class="confirm-btn">
    Continue

    <svg class="btn-icon"
         xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
         viewBox="0 -960 960 960"
         fill="currentColor">

        <path d="M647-440H160v-80h487L423-744l57-56 320 320-320 320-57-56 224-224Z"/>
    </svg>
</button>
```

CSS:

```css
.confirm-btn {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;
}

.btn-icon {
    width: 20px;
    height: 20px;
    fill: currentColor;
}
```

This is actually what I'd use in Arthur Core because:

* No Google dependency
* No extra HTTP request
* Works offline
* Works in Kubernetes
* Works in Thymeleaf
* Easy to recolor with CSS

---

### Option 3 - Material Symbols (if your architects want Google's icon set)

Add in `<head>`:

```html
<link rel="stylesheet"
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Material+Symbols+Outlined" />
```

Button:

```html
<button type="submit" class="confirm-btn">
    Continue
    <span class="material-symbols-outlined">
        arrow_forward
    </span>
</button>
```

But for an enterprise app deployed through Arthur Core, I'd choose **Option 2 (inline SVG)**. It's the most robust and easiest to maintain.
